message.content:
For a graph of the line $2x + y = 6$, we can plot the $x$-intercept, $(3,0)$ and the $y$-intercept, $(0,6)$.  When $x=0$, we can see that $y=6$, and when $y=0$, we have $2x=6$ so $x=3$.  Therefore the line passes through $(0,6)$ and $(3,0)$.  To determine the area of the triangular region enclosed by the axes and the line, we calculate \[\frac12 \cdot (\text{base}) \cdot (\text{height}).\][asy]
size(6cm);
fill((0, 0)--(3, 0)--(0,6)--cycle, gray(0.8));
draw((-1,0)--(4,0), Arrow);
draw((0,-1)--(0,7), Arrow);
draw((0,-1)--(0,7), linewidth(0.7));
draw((4,0)--(-1.5,7/3), linewidth(0.7));
fill((3, 0)--(0,0)--(0,6)--cycle, white);
draw((0,0)--(0, 6), linetype("6 6"), linewidth(0.7));
draw((0,0)--(3, 0), linetype("6 6"), linewidth(0.7));
draw((0,6)--(0, 6.6), linewidth(0.7));
draw((3, 0)--(3.5,0), linewidth(0.7));
label("$x$", (4, 0), E);
label("$y$", (0, 7), N);
label("$O$", (0, 0), SW);
label("$(3,0)$", (3, 0), S);
label("$(0, 6)$", (0, 6), W);
[/asy]

Both the base and the height of the triangle are given by the line $2x + y = 6$.  When $x=0$, the line is at $y=6$, so the height of the triangle is $6$.  When $y=0$, the line is at $2x=6$, or $x=3$.  Thus the base of the triangle is $3$.  Since $\frac12 \cdot 3 \cdot 6 = \boxed{9}$, the area of the shaded triangle is $9$ square units.
